          "body": "Proverbs 20:22 is the chapter's pastoral climax and one of the most explicitly theological verses in the entire chapter: 'Do not say, I will repay evil; wait for the LORD, and He will save you.' The prohibition is not merely against retaliation — it is against the inner speech that prepares for it ('do not say'). The vengeance impulse begins in the heart before it reaches the hand; the proverb intercepts it there. The positive command — *qavah*, to wait, to hope with expectant confidence — is the verb used across the Psalter for Israel's orientation toward God in distress (Psalm 27:14; 37:34; Isaiah 40:31). The promise 'He will save you' (*yasah*, the same root as *Yeshua*) anchors the command in God's character as Deliverer. This verse sits at the chapter's center of gravity because it addresses the domain where wisdom is most difficult: not the marketplace or the royal court, but the moment of personal injury when self-sovereignty rises most naturally. Romans 12:17-19 quotes Deuteronomy 32:35 and applies the same logic: vengeance belongs to the LORD; the believer's posture is patient trust."
