        "title": "Intoxication, conflict, and the fool who cannot restrain himself",
        "range": "20:1-4",
        "excerpt": "Wine is a mocker, strong drink a brawler, and whoever is intoxicated by it is not wise.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with one of Proverbs' sharpest verdicts on alcohol. The proverb does not say wine is evil in itself — Proverbs elsewhere acknowledges wine as a gift that gladdens the heart (cf. Psalm 104:15). What it says is that wine is a *luts* (mocker) and strong drink is a *hamah* (brawler). The verbs are attributed not to the drinker but to the substances themselves — a form of personification that assigns alcohol the character of its worst effects. The person led astray (*shagah*, to reel, to wander off course) by it 'is not wise' — the passive voice and negative formulation are deliberate understatements. To be led astray by drink is the opposite of wisdom's self-governance.\n\nVerse 2 pivots immediately to royal authority — the king whose anger is a lion's roar. The connection to verse 1 is subtler than it appears: both proverbs deal with self-governance under threat of destruction. The drunkard loses self-governance to alcohol; the provocateur loses his life to the king's anger. In both cases, failure to read the situation accurately — to know what you are dealing with — costs everything. Verse 3 extends the theme: keeping away from strife is *kavod* (honor, weight, glory), while the *evil* (the morally thick fool of Proverbs, not merely the simpleton) will always quarrel. The contrast is between the man who has enough inner strength to walk away and the man who is driven by his passions to escalate.\n\nVerse 4 narrows to a specific instance of self-governance failure: the *atsel* (sluggard) who does not plow in the autumn plowing season and therefore has nothing at harvest. The verse is not a lesson about farming technique — it is a lesson about the inability to connect present action to future consequence. The sluggard's poverty is not accidental; it is the mathematically predictable outcome of present passivity. Proverbs consistently presents the sluggard as a figure not of laziness alone but of temporal blindness — he cannot see the end from the beginning (cf. 6:6-11; 24:30-34).\n\nReading verses 1-4 together: the opening cluster establishes that folly is fundamentally a failure of self-governance — over appetite (v.1), over conflict-instinct (v.3), and over time-perception (v.4). The king of verse 2 is present precisely because the threat of external authority is sometimes the only restraint that works on those who lack internal restraint. The wisdom tradition does not romanticize human self-discipline; it knows it requires both inner formation and external accountability.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Luts* (mocker) is the standard Proverbs term for the scoffer who is beyond instruction (cf. 1:22; 9:7-8); attributing it to wine gives alcohol the character of Proverbs' most unteachable character type. *Shagah* (led astray) is used of animals wandering from the path and of the morally deluded — it combines the ideas of disorientation and culpable wandering."
