        "excerpt": "Do not say, 'I will repay evil'; wait for the LORD, and He will save you.",
        "body": "Verses 18-25 form the chapter's most pastorally urgent cluster, dealing with the consequences of unguarded speech in four domains: strategic counsel (v.18), gossip (v.19), parental honor (v.20), inheritance-rushing (v.21), vengeance-speech (v.22), dishonest commerce again (v.23), divine sovereignty over human steps (v.24), and rash vows (v.25).\n\nVerse 18 establishes the baseline: plans (*machashavah*) are established by *etsah* (counsel, consultation), and war requires *tachbulah* (wise guidance — a nautical term, 'steering ropes,' the wisdom needed to navigate a ship). Even the most decisive human action — military conflict — requires taking counsel before acting. The proverb is an implicit warning against self-reliance in high-stakes decisions. Verse 19 follows immediately: the *rakhil* (slanderer, gossip) who 'reveals *sod* (secrets)' is both morally dangerous and identifiable — he is a 'constant gossip' (*halakh rakhil*, literally 'a going-about tale-bearer'). The command is explicit: do not associate with him. The connection to verse 18 is meaningful — counsel requires confidential trust, and the gossip destroys the very condition counsel requires.\n\nVerse 20 issues one of Proverbs' most solemn verdicts: the person who *qalal* (curses, makes light of, despises) his father or mother will have his *ner* (lamp) extinguished in deepest *choshekh* (darkness). The lamp-image is the chapter's symbol of life and divine blessing (it returns in v.27). To curse one's parents is to strike at the foundational social order the wisdom tradition upholds; it is the household equivalent of provoking the king in verse 2. The consequence — lamp extinguished in deepest darkness — is the chapter's most vivid image of comprehensive desolation: not merely poverty or social disgrace, but the total absence of the light that orients human life.\n\nVerse 22 is the cluster's pastoral climax: 'Do not say, I will repay evil; wait for the LORD, and He will save you.' The prohibition targets the inner speech that precedes retaliation — not merely the act of vengeance but the resolve to commit it. The command to *qavah* (wait, hope with expectant confidence) in the LORD is among Proverbs' most explicit theological imperatives. John Owen observed that the temptation to personal vengeance is strongest precisely when the injury is most legitimate — when the wrong done to us is real and our desire for justice is righteous. The proverb does not dismiss the desire for justice; it redirects its execution to the LORD.\n\nVerse 25 closes the cluster with the rash vow: 'It is a trap for a man to say rashly, It is holy!' The word *moqesh* (trap, snare) is used of the devices that catch animals — the rash vow is a self-set trap. *Qodesh* (holy, dedicated to God) was a technical term for property consecrated to the temple; to declare something *qodesh* in an impulsive moment and then reconsider is precisely the sequence Ecclesiastes 5:2-5 warns against and Leviticus 27 regulates.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qavah* (wait, v.22) is the same verb Isaiah uses in the great eschatological promise of 40:31: 'Those who wait for the LORD will gain new strength.' It carries the sense of hopeful, taut expectation — like a rope stretched toward its anchor. *Toevah* reappears in v.23 deliberately — the double occurrence in one chapter (vv.10 and 23) functions as a literary frame around the marketplace material."
